<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="323" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="323">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="323">
The original description of 
<taxonomicName family="Scelionidae" genus="G." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="G. geminum" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="323" rank="species" species="geminum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="323">G. geminum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is so sparse that it can hardly be considered a description. It merely states that this species differs from 
<taxonomicName family="Scelionidae" genus="G." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="G. austini" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="323" rank="species" species="austini">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="323">G. austini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the sculpture of the frons, but with no mention of how it is different. This approach to species descriptions is of no benefit and has created significant obstacles for advancing taxonomy in this group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
